As Sera wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/18/2004 at 03:12:38 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>If the lengths of the sides of a square are doubled, is the area 
>doubled? Why or why not?

If L is the length of a side of the square then 

            Area = L^2

If we double the lengths of the sides of a square

         New Area = (2L) x (2L)

                  =  4L^2

                  = 4 x original area.

So if you double the sides you increase the area by a factor of 4.


